### ‚úÖ What is **Prototype** in JavaScript?

In JavaScript, **prototype** is the mechanism by which **objects inherit properties and methods from other objects**.

***

## üîπ Simple Definition (Interview‚Äëready)

> A **prototype** is an object from which other objects inherit properties and methods in JavaScript.

***

## üîπ Key Idea to Remember

‚úÖ JavaScript uses **prototype‚Äëbased inheritance**  
‚úÖ Every object has an internal link to another object called its **prototype**  
‚úÖ This link forms a **prototype chain**

***

## üîπ Two Important Terms (Very Important üî•)

### 1Ô∏è‚É£ `__proto__` (internal / instance side)

*   Exists on **every JavaScript object**
*   Points to the object‚Äôs prototype

### 2Ô∏è‚É£ `prototype` (constructor side)

*   Exists **only on constructor functions**
*   Used as a blueprint for objects created with `new`

***

## ‚úÖ Basic Example

```js
const obj = {};
```

Prototype chain:

    obj ‚Üí Object.prototype ‚Üí null

```js
obj.toString(); // works
```

‚úÖ `toString()` comes from `Object.prototype`

***

## ‚úÖ Constructor Function Example

```js
function Person(name) {
  this.name = name;
}

Person.prototype.greet = function () {
  console.log("Hello " + this.name);
};

const p1 = new Person("Raja");
```

### üîπ Prototype Chain

    p1
     ‚Üì __proto__
    Person.prototype
     ‚Üì __proto__
    Object.prototype
     ‚Üì
    null

‚úÖ `p1.greet()` works because of prototype lookup

***

## üîç How Property Lookup Works (Very Important)

When you access a property:

```js
p1.greet();
```

JavaScript looks in this order:

1.  `p1` object
2.  `Person.prototype`
3.  `Object.prototype`
4.  `null` ‚Üí stop

‚úÖ First match wins

***

## ‚úÖ `prototype` vs `__proto__` (Classic Interview Question)

```js
p1.__proto__ === Person.prototype; // ‚úÖ true
```

| Term        | Belongs To  | Purpose                 |
| ----------- | ----------- | ----------------------- |
| `prototype` | Constructor | Blueprint for instances |
| `__proto__` | Object      | Points to its prototype |

***

