## ‚úÖ Inheritance Using Prototype (`extends`)

```js
class Employee extends Person {
  work() {
    console.log("Working");
  }
}

const e = new Employee();
```

Prototype chain:

    e
     ‚Üì
    Employee.prototype
     ‚Üì
    Person.prototype
     ‚Üì
    Object.prototype
     ‚Üì
    null

‚úÖ This is how JavaScript achieves inheritance

***

## ‚úÖ Object.create() (Direct Prototype Control)

```js
const parent = {
  greet() {
    console.log("Hello");
  }
};

const child = Object.create(parent);
```

Prototype chain:

    child ‚Üí parent ‚Üí Object.prototype ‚Üí null

‚úÖ No constructor needed  
‚úÖ Very clean prototype inheritance

***

## üî• Why Prototype Is Important

‚úÖ Memory efficiency (methods shared)  
‚úÖ Inheritance  
‚úÖ Method reuse  
‚úÖ Foundation of `class` and `extends`  
‚úÖ Understanding bugs & performance

***

## ‚úÖ Common Interview Traps

### ‚ùì Is prototype copying?

‚ùå No ‚Äî it's **referencing**, not copying

***

### ‚ùì Do all objects have a prototype?

‚úÖ Yes (except objects created with `Object.create(null)`)

***

### ‚ùì Is prototype the same as class?

‚ùå No ‚Äî **classes use prototypes internally**

***

## ‚úÖ One‚ÄëLine Interview Answer

> Prototype is the mechanism by which JavaScript objects inherit properties and methods from other objects through a prototype chain.

***

## ‚úÖ 10‚ÄëSecond Interview Explanation

> Every JavaScript object has a prototype, and when a property is not found on the object, JavaScript looks up the prototype chain until it finds the property or reaches null.

***

## ‚úÖ Real‚ÄëWorld Tip (React / JS)

*   Many bugs happen due to **prototype shadowing**
*   Understanding prototypes helps debug `undefined is not a function`
*   Libraries & frameworks rely heavily on prototypes

