# ‚úÖ 1. Basic Prototype Example

```javascript
function Person(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
}

// Adding method to prototype
Person.prototype.greet = function () {
    return `Hello, my name is ${this.name}`;
};

const p1 = new Person("Ravi", 25);
const p2 = new Person("Anu", 30);

console.log(p1.greet()); // Hello, my name is Ravi
console.log(p2.greet()); // Hello, my name is Anu
```

üëâ **Key point:**  
Methods added to `prototype` are **shared across all instances** (memory efficient).

***

# ‚úÖ 2. Prototype Chain Example

```javascript
function Animal(name) {
    this.name = name;
}

Animal.prototype.speak = function () {
    return `${this.name} makes a noise`;
};

function Dog(name, breed) {
    Animal.call(this, name); // inherit properties
    this.breed = breed;
}

// Inherit prototype
Dog.prototype = Object.create(Animal.prototype);
Dog.prototype.constructor = Dog;

// Add new method
Dog.prototype.bark = function () {
    return `${this.name} barks`;
};

const d1 = new Dog("Bruno", "Labrador");

console.log(d1.speak()); // Bruno makes a noise
console.log(d1.bark());  // Bruno barks
```

üëâ **Key concepts:**

*   `Object.create()` ‚Üí sets up prototype chain
*   Child inherits parent methods

***

# ‚úÖ 3. Override Prototype Method (Polymorphism)

```javascript
Dog.prototype.speak = function () {
    return `${this.name} barks loudly`;
};

console.log(d1.speak()); // Bruno barks loudly
```

üëâ Method overriding works via prototype chain.

***

# ‚úÖ 4. Using ES6 Classes (Behind the scenes uses prototypes)

```javascript
class Person {
    constructor(name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    greet() {
        return `Hi, I'm ${this.name}`;
    }
}

const p = new Person("Rajashekar");

console.log(p.greet());
```

üëâ Internally:

*   `greet()` is stored in `Person.prototype`

***

# ‚úÖ 5. Checking Prototype

```javascript
console.log(p.__proto__ === Person.prototype); // true
console.log(Person.prototype.isPrototypeOf(p)); // true
```

***

# ‚úÖ 6. Adding Property Dynamically

```javascript
Person.prototype.country = "India";

console.log(p1.country); // India
console.log(p2.country); // India
```

***

# ‚úÖ 7. Important Interview Points

*   Every JS object has a hidden `[[Prototype]]`
*   Functions have a `prototype` property
*   `new` keyword does:
    1.  Creates a new object
    2.  Sets prototype
    3.  Binds `this`
    4.  Returns object
*   Prototype enables **inheritance + code reuse**

***

